## Example 1 — Continuous Exponential Growth

In `2016`, the population of Florida was `20.61` million people. In `2000`, it was `15.98` million.

### Part A: Write an exponential growth equation

Use:

`y = ae^(kt)`

Since `t` is years after `2000`:

* `a = 15.98`
* `y = 20.61` when `t = 16`

Substitute:

`20.61 = 15.98e^(16k)`

Divide by `15.98`:

`20.61 / 15.98 = e^(16k)`

Take natural logarithms:

`ln(20.61 / 15.98) = 16k`

Solve:

`k = ln(20.61 / 15.98) / 16`

`k ≈ 0.0159`

So the model is:

`y = 15.98e^(0.0159t)`

### Part B: Predict when the population will reach `25` million people

Substitute `y = 25`:

`25 = 15.98e^(0.0159t)`

`1.564 = e^(0.0159t)`

Take natural logarithms:

`ln 1.564 = 0.0159t`

`t = ln 1.564 / 0.0159`

`t ≈ 28.129`

Florida’s population reaches `25` million about `28.129` years after `2000`, or in `2028`.

### Part C: Compare the populations of Florida and California

California’s population in `2000` was `33.9` million and can be modeled by:

`y = 33.9e^(0.0092t)`

Determine when Florida’s population will surpass California’s.

Set up the inequality:

`15.98e^(0.0159t) > 33.9e^(0.0092t)`

Take natural logarithms:

`ln 15.98 + 0.0159t > ln 33.9 + 0.0092t`

Subtract `0.0092t`:

`ln 15.98 + 0.0067t > ln 33.9`

Subtract `ln 15.98`:

`0.0067t > ln 33.9 - ln 15.98`

Solve:

`t > (ln 33.9 - ln 15.98) / 0.0067`

`t > 112.25`

So, if the trend continues, Florida is on track to surpass California in `2112`.

## Think About It

Based on the given models, does it make sense that Florida’s population will eventually surpass California’s? Explain.

